    Research Article| December 01, 2012

    The Tectonomagmatic Source of Ore Metals and Volatile Elements in the Southern Kermadec Arc

    R. J. Wysoczanski;
    M. R. Handler;
    C. I. Schipper;
    M. I. Leybourne;
    J. Creech;
    M. D. Rotella;
    A.R.L. Nichols;
    C.J.N. Wilson;
    R. B. Stewart
    Author and Article Information
    Economic Geology (2012) 107 (8): 1539–1556.
    https://doi.org/10.2113/econgeo.107.8.1539
    Article history
    • Standard View
    • Open the PDF for in another window
    • Cite
    • Share Icon Share

    Abstract

    Deciphering the ultimate source of chalcophile metals (e.g., Cu, Zn, Pb) in volcanogenic massive sulfide (VMS) deposits and the volatiles that help drive their formation is critical for understanding where, how, and why VMS deposits form. The southern Kermadec arc volcanic front is known to be highly hydrothermally active and host to at least three VMS deposits, whereas the associated back -arc system is apparently hydrothermally inactive, although this may simply be due to a lack of exploration in this region. We have analyzed major, trace, and volatile element concentrations in a suite of basaltic glasses and olivine-hosted melt inclusions from volcanoes, ridges, and rifts of the southern Kermadec arc volcanic front and Havre Trough back-arc basin. These data indicate clear compositional differences in the mantle beneath the arc front and the back arc, with the arc front having higher extents of prior melt extraction and enrichment in volatile and metal elements from slab-derived aqueous fluids. The magmatic budget of Pb is supplied to the mantle source by these slab-derived fluids, whereas magmatic concentrations of Zn and Cu are primarily controlled by the degree of partial melting, with a Cu-bearing residual phase required in the mantle. Consequently, the relative enrichment of chalcophile metals in the mantle-derived melts is Pb >> Cu > Zn.

    The magma volatile history recorded by the glasses and melt inclusions indicates that degassing during crystal fractionation is significant and, notably, leads to the reduction of sulfur in the evolving magma as oxidized sulfur degasses preferentially. The apparent absence (or retention) of volatiles (notably CO2 and SO3) in magma chambers, lack of magmatic activity, and absence of hot, mafic dikes beneath volcanoes may be important factors in inhibiting the formation of active hydrothermal venting, and by extension the potential for VMS deposition.

    Introduction

    Volcanogenic massive sulfide (VMS) deposits in oceanic subduction zone settings, including the Kermadec arc and Havre Trough, are seen as a valuable commodity and may be viable as a source of base metals (Rona, 2008; Fouquet and Scott, 2009; Hoagland et al., 2010). However, the ultimate source of sulfur and metals in VMS deposits is the topic of significant discussion in the literature. In particular, are volatile elements (e.g., S, H, C, and Cl) and VMS-associated metals (such as the chalcophile elements Pb, Zn, and Cu) ultimately sourced from slab-derived components in subduction zone settings, or are they sourced from the ambient mantle (i.e., the mantle prior to the addition of slab-derived components), similar to hydrothermal venting and VMS deposit generation at divergent plate boundaries?

    Here, we present volatile, major and trace element data from glasses and olivine-hosted melt inclusions from basalts recovered along the southern Kermadec arc and Havre Trough northeast of New Zealand, to address the relationships between magmatic composition, hydrothermal venting, and the sources of metals and volatiles in subduction-related VMS deposits. Only melt inclusions in olivine are discussed here, as these represent the chemical composition of the crystallizing melt prior to extensive differentiation (as olivine is one of the first minerals to crystallize from the melt). As these inclusions were also trapped at depth, they retain undegassed or (at a minimum) less degassed magmatic volatile contents than erupted lavas and can provide constraints on magma chamber pressures and processes. Pillow rim glasses represent the final quenched melt phase and allow precise measurement of a large range of elements that can be used to address the relationship between volatile and metallic elements during eruption. Comparison of volatile species between melt inclusions and pillow glasses also allows the nature of degassing to be traced from magma chamber to the eruption, providing insights into the role of magmatic gases in driving hydrothermal systems.

    Geologic Setting and Sampling

    The Kermadec arc (Fig. 1) is an intra-oceanic subduction system with the Tonga (Tofua) arc to the north and continental New Zealand to the south (e.g., Smith and Price, 2006; Graham et al., 2008). Although a continuous arc system, the boundary between the Tonga and Kermadec arc is considered to occur at ~25°36' S, where the Louisville seamount chain subducts beneath the Australian Plate. Here, the Lau Basin, back arc to the Tofua arc, becomes the Havre Trough, which is back arc to the Kermadec arc. To the south, subduction changes from the oceanic Kermadec arc and Havre Trough to the continental Taupo Volcanic Zone of New Zealand.

    The Kermadec arc and Havre Trough are bounded to the west and east by the Colville and Kermadec ridges, respectively. These represent the remnants of the Eocene-Pliocene Lau-Colville arc, which was active at least 17 m.y. (Mortimer et al., 2010). This arc was subsequently split by the opening of the Havre Trough at ~5.5 Ma (Parson and Wright, 1996). Opening of the Havre Trough is considered to reflect extensional rifting (i.e., thinning of preexisting crust, e.g., Wright et al., 1996). However, the occurrence of deep (>4,000 m) basins with axial ridges that represent recent or current magmatic activity led Wysoczanski et al. (2010) to suggest that the Havre Trough is in a state of “disorganized” spreading (i.e., growth of new crust) similar to that occurring in the Valu Fa Ridge to the north (Martinez and Taylor, 2006). This supports an earlier interpretation by Malahoff et al. (1982), based on aeromagnetic anomalies, that the Havre Trough is undergoing spreading. Volcanoes of the present-day Kermadec arc, which has been active for at least the last 2 m.y. (Mortimer et al., 2010), straddle the Kermadec Ridge in its northern part but occur progressively more west of the ridge toward the south.

    Volcanism in the Kermadec arc and Havre Trough is largely of basaltic to basaltic-andesitic composition (Gamble et al., 1993; Wright et al., 1996), although silicic magmatism is becoming more commonly recognized along the arc front (Wright et al., 2006), particularly in calderas situated on thicker crust, similar to other oceanic arcs (e.g., Tamura and Wysoczanski, 2006). Hydrothermal activity occurs at the majority of arc-front volcanoes in the Kermadec arc, with more than twothirds of southern Kermadec arc volcanoes host to hydrothermal venting (de Ronde et al., 2007). To date, no hydrothermal activity has been found in the Havre Trough (Leybourne et al., 2012), despite the back arc comprising >60% of the Kermadec arc and Havre Trough, compared to 4% for arc-front volcanoes by area (Wysoczanski and Clark, in press). Although the Kermadec arc is characterized by high levels of hydrothermal activity, only three hydrothermally active volcanoes are known to host VMS deposits, namely, Clark, Brothers, and Rumble II West (de Ronde et al., 2005, 2011, in prep.). Two VMS deposits (at Volcanoes 1 and 19) also occur in the Tofua arc (Stoffers et al., 2006). It should be noted, however, that the distribution of VMS deposits in the Kermadec arc and Havre Trough and hydrothermal venting in the Havre Trough is poorly constrained due to limited exploration.

    Basaltic samples analyzed here come from the southern Kermadec arc and Havre Trough, where sampling of both arc and back-arc features has been focused. They include samples from both the arc-front volcanoes and back-arc basins, and from hydrothermally active and inactive volcanoes. Sample locations and physical characteristics are given in Table 1 and Figure 1. The arc-front volcanoes sampled, from north to south, include Rumble II West, Rumble II East, Rumble III, Rumble IV, and Clark (Fig. 1). Of these, Rumble II West, Rumble III, and Clark are known to be hydrothermally active (de Ronde et al., 2001, 2007, in prep.; Leybourne et al., 2012). A basaltic sample from a ridge northeast of Brothers volcano (which hosts a well-studied VMS deposit; de Ronde et al., 2005, 2011) has also been analyzed, as well as one sample from the Kermadec Ridge (Fig. 1). Back-arc samples come from the Ngatoroirangi Rift (samples 986-6 and 987-9 previously reported by Wysoczanski et al. (2010) and Todd et al. (2011)) and from the Havre Tough at ~34°30' S (sample PPTUW/5; first reported by Gamble et al. (1993); see Fig. 1).

    Analytical Methods

    Pillow rim glasses from all samples were washed and crushed with a mortar and pestle. Where possible, olivine crystals were picked by hand from the glass samples as melt inclusions from quenched pillow rims are less likely to have crystallized. Where insufficient melt inclusion-bearing olivine was available in the glass separates, olivine from pillow lavas was separated by crushing the rock in a jaw crusher and separating olivine using sodium polytungstate. Olivine from the Clark Volcano did not contain uncrystallized melt inclusions of sufficient size, and the samples from the Kermadec Ridge and Brothers NE Ridge were not sampled for melt inclusions. Fresh glass chips and melt inclusion-bearing olivine were mounted individually in Crystalbond™ 509, and ground and polished using 400- and 1,200-grit silica carbide paper and 3- and 1-μm diamond paper following the procedure of Nichols and Wysoczanski (2007).

    Glass samples from the Ngatoroirangi Rift and sample PPTUW/5 from the Havre Trough were analyzed for water and CO2 species on a Varian FTS 7000 Fourier transform infrared (FTIR) spectrometer at the Japan Agency for Marine Earth Science and Technology. All other samples were analyzed on a Nicolet 6700 FTIR at the Department of Soil and Earth Sciences, Massey University. Glass chips were analyzed as doubly polished wafers, whereas melt inclusions were analyzed on a single polished surface, The effect of the olivine host was removed using spectral bands diagnostic of olivine, following the method of Nichols and Wysoczanski (2007). This technique vastly simplifies sample preparation as only one side of the inclusion needs be exposed, allowing for ease of handling and the ability to prepare more samples in a given time.

    Water intensity was measured at the 3,550 -cm−1 stretching vibration (total water) and the 1,630-cm−1 vibration (molecular water). Carbon was measured at the 1,520- and 1,440-cm−1 doublet. Molar absorptivities used to calculate volatile concentrations were: 63 l mol−1 cm−1 for the 3,550-cm−1 band (Dixon et al., 1995), 28 l mol−1 cm−1 for the 1,630−cm−1 band (Dixon et al., 1995), and 375 l mol−1 cm−1 for the CO3 doublet bands (Fine and Stolper, 1985), respectively. Glass densities were calculated from the chemical composition of the glass (Luhr, 2001). Sample thicknesses were determined using reflection spectra as outlined by Wysoczanski and Tani (2006), which is significantly more accurate and precise than optical or micrometer methods for thin wafers (between 8−94 μm). Water and carbon species concentrations were then determined by applying the Beer-Lambert law (see Ihinger et al., 1994, for details). OH– was determined as the difference between total and molecular water.

    Major element contents of pillow glass, melt inclusions, and host olivine were analyzed using a JEOL JXA-8230 electron probe microanalyzer (EPMA) at Victoria University of Wellington. Beam conditions were a 15-kV accelerating voltage, 8-nA beam current, and a defocused spot (10-μm spot size) for glass compositions, and 20-kV, 20-nA, and a focused spot for olivine analyses. Analytical precision and reproducibility were monitored by analyzing the MPI-DING glass standard KL2-G (Jochum et al., 2006) and the Smithsonian standard Springwater Olivine (Jarosewich et al., 1980). All samples were analyzed multiple times, corrected to the secondary standards, and averaged. The precision and reproducibility of these standards is reported in Table 2. To account for crystallization of olivine in melt inclusions, the host olivine composition was added to the melt inclusion composition until an olivine-melt KdFe-Mg of 0.3 was reached (Roeder and Emslie, 1970), using the method of Luhr (2001).

    Sulfur speciation for all samples was determined from the position of the SKa peak wavelength determined by EPMA. The position of the sulfur peak for unknown samples was determined and its speciation (i.e., the ratio of oxidized:reduced S, reported as % S6+) calculated from its position relative to that of oxidized (celestine) and reduced (galena) standards. For a full account of this method, see Carroll and Rutherford (1988), Wallace and Carmichael (1994), and Rowe et al. (2007).

    Trace element concentrations were determined using a New Wave deep UV (193nm) laser ablation (LA) system coupled to an Agilent 7500CS inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometer (ICPMS) at Victoria University of Wellington. Analyses were obtained on the same part of the glass shards analyzed for major element concentrations. The analytical method follows that described in Allan et al. (2008). Following EPMA analysis, the sample mounts were lightly polished to remove all traces of the carbon coat. Sample mounts were loaded in the sample chamber together with a standard glass, BCR-2G, which was used for calibration and monitoring drift throughout the run. All data were acquired as static spot analyses using a laser spot diameter of 50 μm, and the laser beam set to 5 Hz and 65% power. Thirty-nine minor and trace elements were measured. A minor isotope of Ca (43Ca) was also measured and used as an internal standard for each analysis, using the EPMA Ca data for that glass.

    Results

    Major and trace elements

    All samples are basaltic to basaltic-andesite in composition, and show a strong negative correlation of SiO2 with MgO (Tables 3, 4; Fig. 2). Notably, melt inclusions have higher MgO contents than their host pillow rim samples, indicative of their less evolved composition and showing that the host melt has evolved through fractionation of olivine (and possibly other phases) since the inclusions were entrapped.

    Arc-front samples are characterized by lower TiO2 and Na2O contents, at similar MgO content (Fig. 2), compared to back-arc samples. Rumble II East melt inclusions are the most depleted in these elements. A number of Clark samples also have low TiO2 and Na2O and are notable in their highly elevated K2O, which also distinguishes the high K whole-rock suite of Clark Volcano samples (Gamble et al., 1997). The two ridge samples (Brothers NE and Kermadec Ridge) are among the most evolved samples analyzed (i.e., Mg no. = 39.8 and 32.8, respectively).

    All samples show large-ion lithophile element (LILE)-enriched trace element contents typical of subduction lavas (e.g., Gill, 1981), with strong Pb and Sr enrichments and Ta, Nb, Zr, and Hf depletions (Fig. 3a). Although back-arc samples share these features, in general they have lower LILE enrichment and are less high field strength element (HSFE) depleted than arc-front samples, with back-arc HFSE contents similar to mid-ocean ridge basalt (MORB). These features are most evident in Clark samples, which show the highest trace element contents. However, they also have unusually high Rb (and K) contents, the lowest Pb and Sr enrichment (relative to other LILE in the sample), and the most pronounced negative Hf and Zr anomalies (relative to other HSFE). Clark samples also have significantly higher ratios of light rare earth elements (LREE) to heavy rare earth elements (HREE) compared to other samples (e.g., Ce/Yb = ~25 vs. <10). Rumble II East samples are unusual in their highly depleted trace element contents compared to all other samples (especially in HFSE and HREE). Notably they have the largest Nb and Ta depletion and, despite having the lowest TiO2 contents (Fig. 2), Ti is not as depleted as other HFSE (Fig. 3a). Rumble II East REE contents are also the lowest (and have the flattest patterns) of all samples analyzed here (Fig. 3b). Brothers and Kermadec Ridge samples are similar to other arc-front samples, except that they are among the most LILE and LREE enriched (together with Clark), although they are also some of the most evolved (i.e., have some of the lowest MgO values; Fig. 2).

    Chlorine contents in all Kermadec arc and Havre Trough samples show a strong negative correlation with MgO, confirming that chlorine is an incompatible element during fractionation and does not degas before, or during, eruption (Kent et al., 2002; Wysoczanski et al., 2006; Sun et al., 2007; de Ronde et al., 2011). The strong trend of Cl with MgO (Fig. 2) and other elements (e.g., K2O) also indicates that the magmas have not interacted significantly with hydrothermal brines, or seawater.

    Volatiles and sulfur speciation

    All glass samples have water contents corresponding to saturation at their depth of collection (using the VolatileCalc program of Newman and Lowenstern, 2002) and, except for Rumble IV glasses, contain no detectable CO2, indicative of extensive degassing (Fig. 4a). With the exception of sample PPTUW/5, melt inclusions have higher water contents than matrix glasses from the same sample and most contain detectable CO2. Taken as a whole, glass and melt inclusion water contents show a curvilinear trend of decreasing H2O (indicating degassing) with decreasing MgO (indicating fractionation) from melt inclusions to pillow glasses. This is consistent with degassing-driven fractional crystallization occurring during the ascent of water-saturated magmas. The exception is sample PPTUW/5 from the Havre Tough that has a glass water content just below saturation for the depth of collection (1.4 wt % H2O in the pillow glass compared with 1.6 wt % H2O saturation at depth of collection; Newman and Lowenstern, 2002) and higher than the corresponding melt inclusions (~1.1 wt % H2O). This suggests an increase in water content in the glass due to fractional crystallization of this sample (Fig. 2). Note, however, that neither the melt inclusions nor the glass in sample PPTUW/5 contains detectable CO2.

    Sulfur contents in melt inclusions are significantly higher than in the host pillow glasses (Fig. 4). There is a negative curvilinear trend of SO3 content with MgO, similar to the behavior of water (Fig. 2). Sulfur speciation is relatively constant in melt inclusions for all samples, arc and back arc alike, at approximately 20 to 40% S6+ (Figs. 2, 4). Using the equation of Jugo et al. (2005), which equates sulfur speciation in basaltic samples to oxygen fugacity, this corresponds to an oxygen fugacity of ~FMQ + 1 (where FMQ is the fayalite-magnetite-quartz oxygen buffer, and where values are expressed as log units). Rumble II East, however, is significantly more oxidized with an oxygen fugacity of >FMQ +2. Pillow glasses for all measurable samples (except Rumble IV) are more reduced (lower S6+) than melt inclusions with oxygen fugacities equating to values of <FMQ +1 (Fig. 4).

    Discussion

    Composition of the Kermadec arc and Havre Trough mantle

    The mantle source composition and the extent of partial melting ultimately control the budgets of volatile elements and chalcophile metals (e.g., Pb, Zn, Cu) produced by arc magmatism. Thus, understanding the composition of the mantle source, and how elements are added to the mantle wedge by dewatering or melting of the subducted slab (e.g., Gill, 1981) and/or associated sediments, is important in determining how elements associated with VMS deposits become concentrated during subsequent volcanic and hydrothermal processes. The trace element data for the southern Kermadec arc and Havre Trough glasses and melt inclusions show some clear differences in the composition of the mantle source of arc-front and back-arc magmas with respect to both the relative fertility of the sources, and the style and extent of slab-derived metasomatic enrichment. In the Havre Trough (represented by Ngatoroirangi Rift samples and sample PPTUW/5) the back-arc mantle is less depleted than the arc-front mantle (i.e., the back-arc mantle has higher HREE and HFSE contents; Fig. 3) with lower degrees of melting (Fig. 5; Todd et al., 2010, 2012; Timm et al., 2011, 2012). The Kermadec Ridge sample was derived from a relatively undepleted mantle source that underwent a high degree of melting. Conversely, enrichment of LREE and LILE relative to HFSE and HREE is lower in rocks from the back arc compared to those from the arc front, a feature that suggests there is less of a slab component (i.e., enrichment of the mantle wedge by fluids and melt derived from the subducting slab) in the back arc (Fig. 3).

    The transfer of slab-derived elements to the mantle wedge is commonly ascribed to either aqueous fluids (the primary mechanism for fluid-mobile elements such as Cl, Ba, Sr, Pb) or sediment melts (which are able to transport fluid-immobile elements such as the LREE, Hf). Trace element ratios of fluid and melt mobile elements compared to immobile elements can be used to distinguish the relative importance of these two mechanisms in controlling the trace element composition of the mantle wedge.

    The slab component (using the ratios of Ba/Nb to follow fluids, and [La/Sm]n to follow melts; Fig. 5) of southern Kermadec arc and Havre Trough samples indicates that similar sediment melt components are added to the arc and back-arc mantle, ranging from essentially no addition (depleted mantle composition) to sediment melt rich (Fig. 5). Alternatively, the range in [La/Sm]n shown by the glasses and melt inclusions may simply reflect heterogeneity in enrichment or depletion of the mantle wedge (i.e., E-MORB to N-MORB). The Kermadec Ridge sample is especially enriched in both a fluid and melt component and the back-arc Gill Volcano has a high sediment melt component (i.e., approaching the Clark Volcano high K samples) but no appreciable fluid component. The Havre Trough mantle has significantly less fluid component added than the arc-front mantle, as also noted by Wysoczanski et al. (2006) and Todd et al. (2010, 2011). This is exemplified by the amount of melting of the mantle wedge being proportional to the amount of slab fluid added to the mantle wedge (Fig. 5b, see positive covariation of Ba/Nb with degree of melting).

    Petrogenesis of Kermadec arc and Havre Trough volcanic rocks and local slab input

    The Rumble V cross-arc chain is a volcanic ridge extending from Rumble V Volcano in the east, across the width of the Havre Trough to the Colville Ridge in the west (Fig. 1). This unusual feature yields insights into mantle source heterogeneity at consistent latitude, including the role of slab-derived melts and fluids (Todd et al., 2010). Rumble V cross-arc chain lavas contain similar slab components to back-arc lavas with very little fluid component (Fig. 5), although they do show an increase in sediment melt component away from the arc front. A subset of samples (the cross-arc−enriched group, Figs. 5, 6), however, are enriched in both the fluid and sediment melt component (Todd et al., 2010). This suggests that the Havre Trough mantle is locally enriched by a fluid component.

    Arc-front samples (except for the unusual high K Clark samples) show a strong negative relationship between fluid and sediment melt components (Fig. 5a). The most fluid poor end member of the trend coincides with the [La/Sm]n-enriched back-arc samples, suggesting a decrease in fluid component as the sediment melt component increases (or that the degree of mantle depletion decreases). In particular, Gill Volcano, which sits in the center of the back arc, has a slab component more akin to Havre Trough samples than arc-front samples. By contrast, the enriched Rumble V cross chain lavas have compositions more similar to arc-front lavas. This suggests that the mantle beneath the arc front is fluid rich and mantle beneath the back arc is fluid poor, with a sediment melt component (and/or more enriched mantle source) increasing in the mantle away (westward) from the arc front.

    Clark Volcano high K samples and the Kermadec Ridge sample are notable in that they have trace element characteristics indicating both high fluid and melt components, suggesting that the unusual composition of Clark high K lavas may be due to a localized high sediment melt component (or a more enriched mantle source).

    Mantle melt modeling and the source of Pb, Zn, and Cu

    The enrichment of the mantle in metals from slab-derived components can be quantified using the assumption that key metals in VMS deposits (e.g., Pb, Cu, Zn) are initially present in the mantle wedge at ambient mantle values (i.e., depleted mantle abundance), and that any variation from these values can be attributed to other arc magma sources, such as slab-derived fluids or sediment melts (see also Timm et al., 2012). Covariance of metal abundances with sediment melt and fluid indices should help distinguish between these sources. In Figure 5, the ratio of metals to Ce (as an indicator of the enrichment of these metals compared to an assumed immobile element) is compared to fluid and slab components to ascertain any relationship between them. Also shown are the results of fractional melting of a variably enriched mantle source. The models used here are for melting of depleted mantle and for a mantle enriched by 1 and 3% fluid and sediment components, respectively. Modeling with metal-compatible residual phases in the mantle is also shown.

    Compared to mantle values (i.e., N- and E-MORB) Pb/Ce is significantly enriched in all samples, whereas Cu/Ce and Zn/Ce span the range of MORB mantle values (although Rumble II East samples extend to significantly higher values). In arc-front samples, there is a strong positive correlation of Pb/Ce with the fluid component, except for Clark high K samples, which have a higher sediment melt component (Fig. 5c). Enrichment in Pb/Ce is significant, up to 20 times mantle values, indicating that Pb in arc-front samples is almost entirely slab derived, as previously reported by Wysoczanski et al. (2006; see also Timm et al., 2012). With the exception of Rumble II East samples, which have Zn/Ce and Cu/Ce ratios twice that of enriched mantle, Zn and Cu are not significantly added to the mantle wedge by slab-derived fluids. The relationship between metal enrichment and sediment melt components is less certain, with Pb/Ce, Zn/Ce, and Cu/Ce ratios all similar to mantle values. However, metal/Ce enrichment is generally negative when plotted against [La/Sm]n, indicating that large sediment melt components may dilute enrichment of these metals, as is shown in the extreme case of the Clark high K samples (Fig. 5b).

    The correlation of metal enrichment with slab components observed for arc-front samples also holds true for back-arc samples, except for the Ngatoroirangi Rift samples, which show a positive correlation for Pb/Ce and Zn/Ce with sediment melt, despite their low sediment melt component. This would suggest that in the Ngatoroirangi Rift region, both the fluid and ambient mantle are Pb and Zn poor, and that these elements are primarily sourced from sediment melt.

    The relationship between metal/Ce values and slab components for all arc-front samples can be modeled by the melting of ambient mantle enriched by ~1% fluid and sediment melt component for most samples, with a higher slab component needed for the most enriched samples (especially Rumble II East). These models are consistent with previous estimates of slab-derived components in the mantle wedge determined by trace element and isotopic modeling (e.g., Haase et al., 2002; Wysoczanski et al., 2006; Todd et al., 2010, 2011; Timm et al., 2011).

    Partial melting may have the largest effect on the Zn and Cu concentrations of southern Kermadec arc and Havre Trough magmas, however the Pb content of southern Kermadec arc and Havre Trough parental magmas does not appear to be affected by the extent of partial melting (Fig. 6). As previously discussed, the addition of up to 3% slab component can account for the entire variation of Pb in Kermadec arc and Havre Trough samples. A Pb-bearing residual phase is thus not required.

    The behavior of Zn and Cu during mantle melting is, by contrast, significantly influenced by the extent of partial melting, with the Cu content of the partial melt increasing and the Zn content decreasing, with the amount of partial melting. This indicates that Zn behaves as a moderately incompatible element during mantle melting. This behavior may be explained by the presence of a Zn-bearing phase in the mantle that rapidly melts, releasing Zn to the melt. This phase is most likely a hydrous mineral that would preferentially melt, such as amphibole or phlogopite. Copper, however, behaves as a compatible element during fractional melting, with a slight increase in Cu contents in melts formed by higher amounts of partial melting. This requires the presence of a Cu-bearing residual phase in the mantle during partial melting.

    Variations in volatile budgets of the southern Kermadec arc and Havre Trough mantle

    The volatile contents (H2O, SO3, CO2) preserved in pillow lava glasses are consistent with the water depths and pressures at which the samples were collected. This suggests that volatile contents of the lavas were higher but they have degassed so that the volatile content is in equilibrium with the pressure of eruption. In the melt inclusions, volatile contents are generally higher than in the corresponding glass rims, with more H2O and SO3 especially. There is also a small increase in CO2 in the melt inclusions compared to the glass rims, although values (<250 ppm) are still significantly lower than those expected for undegassed arc-front lavas (>3,000 ppm; Wallace, 2005), suggesting that extensive degassing of CO2 has also occurred. If degassing of the magmas during ascent and eruption was open system (Fig. 4), the H2O contents of CO2-bearing melt inclusions are most likely to reflect their original water content; conversely they would represent minimum contents if the inclusions underwent closed-system degassing. The highest H2O content of the CO2-bearing melt inclusions can then be taken as the minimum water content of primary southern Kermadec arc and Havre Trough magmas. That is, ~2.2 to 2.6 wt % H2O for both arc-front and Ngatoroirangi Rift magmas. This conclusion is similar to that of Wysoczanski et al. (2006) who estimated water contents of ~2.5 wt % for southern Kermadec arc and Havre Trough arc magmas. The similar water content of back-arc mantle melts (up to 2 wt %) to arc-front melts, however, requires the addition of water to that region without the characteristic enrichment of mobile elements provided by slab fluids, which are not a significant component of the Havre Trough mantle.

    Sulfur contents in the melt inclusions are significantly higher than in the host pillow glasses, with negative curvilinear trends between SO3 with MgO, suggestive of degassing-driven fractionation during magma ascent (Fig. 2). This degassing trend for SO3 is similar to the behavior of H2O. Sulfur speciation of southern Kermadec arc and Havre Trough samples equates to an oxygen fugacity of ~FMQ +1 (Fig. 7), although Rumble II East is significantly more oxidized with an oxygen fugacity of >FMQ +2 (see above). The oxygen fugacity of the mantle wedge then is only slightly higher than typical MORB mantle, but locally H2O-rich oxidized regions of the mantle do occur (Lee et al., 2010). Pillow glasses for all measurable samples (except Rumble IV) are more reduced than melt inclusions with oxygen fugacities equating to values of <FMQ +1 (Fig. 4). This suggests that sulfur degasses in an oxidized state and that the erupted magma becomes more reduced. This change in oxidation state may have important implications on the composition of hydrothermal fluids and VMS mineralization along submarine arcs and may be a key control on the difference in style of mineralization between submarine arcs and MORs (see also de Ronde et al., 2011).

    Depth to magma chamber based on volatile systematics

    The volatile contents of melt inclusions can also be used to determine the pressure of entrapment and hence the depth to the magma chamber. Taking into account the depth of the water column at the sample site and assuming an average density of arc crust of 2.5 g/cm3, the depth to the magma chamber can be calculated (Table 4). Magma chamber depths for the volcanoes in this study are Rumble II West, 3,300 mbsf (meters below sea floor); Rumble II East, 2,450 mbsf; Rumble III, 2,600 mbsf; and Rumble IV, 2,250 mbsf. These depth estimates are consistent with those of Dziak et al. (2008) and de Ronde et al. (2011) for Brothers volcano (~2,500 mbsl), based on microseismic activity recorded by hydrophones deployed on the caldera seafloor.

    Implications of magma degassing and magma chamber depth for hydrothermal venting and the formation of VMS deposits

    The observations presented here provide constraints on the occurrence of hydrothermal activity, and hence the potential for VMS deposit formation in the southern Kermadec arc and Havre Trough, based on the chemistry of mafic magmas and mineral inclusions.

    In the first instance, one of the most important parameters for the presence and intensity of venting activity is magma chamber depth and volatile content of the magma below the volcano. A shallow magma chamber would allow a greater amount of volatile species to degas than a deep magma chamber, especially for H2O, SO3, and CO2, potentially driving venting and ultimately the formation of VMS deposits (e.g., Resing et al., 2009; de Ronde et al., 2011; Gruen et al., 2012). The saturation pressures of melt inclusions in southern Kermadec arc and Havre Trough samples (Table 4) indicate that the deepest chamber occurs beneath Rumble II West, which is hydrothermally active. Magma chambers for the other volcanoes are at similar depths, although the two hydrothermally inactive volcanoes (Rumble II East and Rumble IV) have the shallowest magma chambers. However, the magmas of the hydrothermally inactive volcanoes have lower CO2 contents than hydrothermally active volcanoes and generally higher SO3 contents. This suggests that these magma chambers have degassed CO2, and retain SO3, so these volatile species may not be being released to influence venting. The degassing of volatiles has previously been interpreted to occur in shallow magma conduits at Brothers volcano, with gas phase separation the source of shallow harmonic tremor (de Ronde et al., 2011). The volatile species data presented here support these interpretations and suggest that degassing of magma chambers plays an important (but not sole) part in hydrothermal venting in the southern Kermadec arc and Havre Trough.

    One mechanism for enhancing degassing of the magma chamber is the increase in volatile contents of the magmas as they crystallize. In a volatile-saturated system, the magma will become oversaturated and degas, with fluid-mobile species being stripped out. If a free volatile phase accumulates, or external factors such as earthquakes, tectonic events, or the injection of new magma into the magma chamber occur, overpressurization will eventuate, resulting in eruption (Blake, 1984). This would allow the magma chamber to return to a state of volatile undersaturation with the cessation of degassing possibly coinciding with a decrease in sea-floor hydrothermal activity. These processes collectively may lead to an episodic nature to the hydrothermal venting, which could explain such features as the punctuated growth of chimneys at Brothers volcano (e.g., de Ronde et al., 2011).

    A complicating physical variable not yet considered is the availability of heat in minor intrusions as a mechanism to drive sea-floor venting. The presence of mafic dikes beneath volcanoes, for example, could provide both a (transient) source of heat and magmatic fluids and a (lasting) zone of permeability to allow those fluids to reach the seafloor. One such dike may exist at Brothers volcano, where the mafic NE ridge is interpreted to run beneath Brothers volcano in the vicinity of the NW caldera vent site (Fig. 8a, de Ronde et al., 2005). This ridge is young in appearance (glassy samples, no Mn coating and no Fe staining) and basaltic in composition, whereas Brothers volcano is dacitic (de Ronde et al., 2005; Haase et al., 2006). Similar ridges extend beneath Rumble II West, another hydrothermally active volcano (Fig. 8b; Leybourne et al., 2012). This relationship between dikes and hydrothermal activity, however, requires further investigation particularly on the relative timing of the dikes and mineralization.
